data.body:

|theme-tesla|smlombardi|6.0.0|
|change-case|wmaurer|1.0.0|;


---

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Create a snippet that needs a dollar sign, such as this one for AngularJS which needs `$analytics` and `$state`:

````js
	"Analytics Event": {
		"prefix": "ae",
		"body": "$analytics.eventTrack('${1:Event}', {category: ${2:$state.current.data.pageTitle}, label: ${3:label});",
		"description": "Add analytics event tracking to a controller."
	}
````
2. The snippet fails silently as is:  It does not show in the snippets menu nor does the prefix work

3. Logic would dictate I need to escape those two dollar signs, but this is flagged as an error:

![2017-05-01_13-49-22](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/835148/25588285/a9798e8a-2e75-11e7-90be-706e7414f8e0.png)

the error tooltip explains how to use $ in snippets.  However, if I save the file with the error:

![screen shot 2017-05-01 at 1 58 59 pm](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/835148/25588469/5d54e922-2e76-11e7-9330-6bbcaac7c881.png)

the snippet works fine.  so the bug is the error detection; the principle works soundly.

data.title: Installing extensions is broken for shared VS Code installs
data.body:
- VSCode Version: 1.10.2 (intentionally behind due to bugs in 1.11)
- OS Version: Ubuntu Server 16.04.2 LTS

**Steps to Reproduce:**

1. User 1 installs extension - files in /tmp are created with permission 755
2. User 2 attempts to install extension

**Expected result:**
Extension is installed for User 1 and User 2

**Encountered result:**
The extension is installed for User 1, User 2 receives the following error:
```
$ code --install-extension ms-vscode.cpptools
Installing...
events.js:160
      throw er; // Unhandled 'error' event
      ^

Error: EACCES: permission denied, open '/tmp/690b692e-e8a9-493f-b802-8089d50ac1b2'
    at Error (native)
```

User 2 can just as easily block User 1 from installing extensions - there is nothing unique about User 1 or User 2.

**Workaround:**
User 1 can manually delete the file (`690b692e-e8a9-493f-b802-8089d50ac1b2` in the above example) from tmp and User 2 will be able to install. With extensions that require a socket, the matching `.sock` file must also be deleted from `/tmp` - in the above example that file would be `vscode-690b692e-e8a9-493f-b802-8089d50ac1b2.sock`.

data.title: gitignored items not excluded from search
data.body:
A possible bug in _use .gitignore to ignore search inside files and folders_ #78.

I have this workspace open in VSCode 1.11:

| Path            | Contents |
| --------------- | -------- |
| /.gitignore     | a.txt    |
| /a.txt          | aaa      |
| /dir/.gitignore | b.txt    |
| /dir/b.txt      | aaa      |

Search for "aaa" with "Use Ignore Files" enabled yields this:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/101152/25580641/c4192f68-2e82-11e7-9546-2f348f144c8c.png)

These two search results shouldn't show up, should they? I've tried this on a workspace where Git repo actually exists (`.git` present) and where it doesn't with the same result.

Repro project: [gitignoresearch.zip](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/files/967908/gitignoresearch.zip)

data.title: Files opened with untitled scheme are closed on save.
data.body:
<!-- Do you have a question? Please ask it on http://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/vscode -->

- VSCode Version: 1.11.2
- OS Version: macOS Sierra 10.12.4

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Create extension to open from an untitled-scheme URI, show new document, save document. Something like this:
```typescript
'use strict';
import * as vscode from 'vscode';
import * as path from 'path';

export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) {

    let disposable = vscode.commands.registerCommand('extension.execTest', () => {
        let untitledURI = vscode.Uri.file(path.join(vscode.workspace.rootPath,'testUntitled.txt')).with({scheme:'untitled'});
        vscode.workspace.openTextDocument(untitledURI).then(doc => {
            vscode.window.showTextDocument(doc).then(editor => {
                editor.document.save().then(success => {
                    console.log(editor.document.uri.toJSON());
                    console.log(`isClosed: ${editor.document.isClosed}`);    
                });
            });
        });
    });

    context.subscriptions.push(disposable);
}

export function deactivate() {
}
```
2. Run the extension. 

Observed behavior:
New file is created and briefly shown in an active editor, but then immediately closes. Document URI still has `untitled` scheme, and is closed after saving (I'm guessing this is the issue). 

Console output:
```json
{
    "fsPath":"/Volumes/Pocket/Test/testUntitled.txt",
    "external":"untitled:/Volumes/Pocket/Test/testUntitled.txt",
    "$mid":1,
    "path":"/Volumes/Pocket/Test/testUntitled.txt",
    "scheme":"untitled"
}
isClosed: true
```

Expected bahavior:
File stays open in the active editor upon saving and document URI scheme changes from `untitled` to `file`. 

In my actual use case, I am creating a new document, adding content, and opening it for editing by the user. Currently, this requires opening the new `untitled` document, showing it in an editor (to get access to `TextEditor.edit()`), making my changes with `TextEdit.replace()`, saving the document, then opening the newly-saved file with the `file` scheme, and finally showing it in an editor. I'm not sure how much of a change this is, but it seems this could be simpler if the same document instance could be maintained through the changes and could remain open in the active editor. An option could be provided on the `TextDocument.save()` method to optionally provide this behavior.
